	<h1>
Co-Operating with Microsoft
</h1>
	<div class="page-title-hline">&nbsp;</div>
	










<!-- MAIN CONTENT AREA - START -->



		<div class="floatright">
			<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="sidebar" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_sidebar --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_sidebar --> <!-- InstanceEndEditable -->

<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Sidebar" --><!-- InstanceEndEditable --><br class="hide" />
			</div>


			<div class="contentcolumn">
				<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="maincontent" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_maincontent --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_maincontent -->

	<div id="entry-375">
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				
<img alt="DSC_4667.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/DSC_4667.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="float: left; margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt;" width="220" height="331" />This time of year often finds undergraduates at a loss. With final exams and convocation finished, students are asking themselves "what's next?" as they ponder the myriad possibilities afforded them by their Concordia degree. Three fortunate students from the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science already know the answer to that tricky question: they're heading to Seattle to work for Microsoft.<br /><br />Justin Horst, Vijeta Patel and Tristan St-Cyr put themselves on the right track for great careers early on when they applied to be part of Concordia's<br />innovative Institute for Co-operative Education. This special work-study program is available to all students in the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science who have high grades and a strong work ethic. With a passion for learning reflected in their marks, Vijeta, Justin and Tristan more than fit the bill. By alternating on-thejob experience with traditional studies in the classroom, the three graduated this June with a winning combination of theoretical reasoning skills and practical know-how. <br /><br />For Microsoft, a global leader in personal and business software, the fact that the three arrive with some serious on-the-job training already under their belts is a definite boon. The company has such a strong belief in preparing university students for work in the real world that they have established a large and widely regarded internship program. Says Heidi Dowling, University and Recruiting Staff Consultant at Microsoft, "The Microsoft internship program is a fantastic way for technical students to gain exposure to the software development process. Interns here have real jobs with real responsibilities. Each intern is assigned to a group and given substantial projects that are related to the work underway at Microsoft... the experience of building skills and knowledge for a future career is very valuable for students." <br /><br />Last year, Tristan St-Cyr became one of the Concordians lucky enough to be part of that very experience when the Co-op program helped him land one of the coveted internships. "It was a great opportunity," he recalls. "I was there for three months with hundreds of other interns from across North America. I really got a feel for what the company is like, what kind of people work for Microsoft, and what their expectations are." Tristan graduated in June with a<br />Bachelors in Software Engineering and says he feels well prepared to return to Microsoft, where he will work as a software development engineer for the data modeling group. <br /><br />Vijeta and Justin were both newcomers to the company when they applied for jobs. Justin's interest was piqued during a career fair held at Concordia last fall. He did an on-site interview and was later asked to head to Redmond, the suburb of Seattle home to the sprawling Microsoft campus, for an on-site interview. Vijeta, who graduated this June with a Bachelors in Software Engineering, started out with a phone interview before heading out west for her own interview. Both recall the selection process as a challenge that was as nerve-wracking as it was exciting and both say that the internships they completed through Concordia's Coop program gave them a competitive advantage in the selection process. <br /><br />Justin, who has just graduated with a Bachelors in Computer Engineering, will make the move to Microsoft in July, to take on the role of software development engineer and tester for the Windows Phone project. Having completed several internships in Montreal-based companies, Justin relished the chance to get an insider's look at what it was really like to work in industry. "Obviously you learn a lot technically on these internships," says Justin, "but the real jewel is the professional experience you get. When you come back to school you can really tell who has been on internships, just by the way they work or write emails, or even coordinate meetings. You're a 22-year-old working with 50-year-olds. They know what they're doing and you pick up a lot. You realize that real education doesn't come out of books -- it's by doing that you truly learn."<br /><br />Vijeta has a similar outlook, explaining that the Internships she had with IBM in Ontario really prepared her for her future career. "When you're in a working environment," she explains, "you're part of the team and you get to learn what it's like to work on an actual product, you go through the software development life cycle with them. I found that was extremely helpful." Vijeta, who had a busy final year at Concordia serving as VP Academic for the Engineering and Computer Science Students' Association, is looking forward to a summer of R&amp;R abroad before moving to Microsoft's headquarters. She will become a software development engineer for the Internet Explorer team. <br /><br />The three are all smiles when they consider what the future will bring to them. Asked how students just starting out in their undergraduate degrees might ensure that they, too, are given such great career-building opportunities, they are unanimous in their answer: be part of Co-op!<br />

			</div>
